<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-335-580  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 335 580.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer  June 1989 v22 n6 p59(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Controlling the Adaptive Suspension Vehicle. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bihari, Thomas E.; Walliser, Thomas M.; Patterson, Mark R.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Adaptive Suspension Vehicle (ASV), an experimental, six-leggedlocally autonomous robot, employs multiprocessor controls to adaptto rough terrain.andP;  Local autonomy allows the vehicle to chooseappropriate foot and body placement to avoid obstacles after theoperator determines the general direction of travel.andP;  The ASVemploys eight Intel 386-120 computers built around a Multibus IIbackplane.andP;  Its software includes a real-time operating system,which manages the multiprocessor, and application programs forsensing, terrain modeling, motion planning and servo control.andO;Legged vehicles can now compete favorably with conventionalvehicles.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     RobotsIntelligent DevicesResearch and DevelopmentMicroprogrammed ControlNavigationComputer-Controlled Switches.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographchart.andO;Caption:   The ASV computer hardware. (chart)The ASV software. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>